            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this link budget calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool implements a classical RF and satellite link budget in
                decibels. It accounts for transmit power, antenna gains,
                free-space path loss, miscellaneous losses, system noise
                temperature, bandwidth, and data rate to estimate received
                power, SNR, Eb/N0, and fade margin.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Free-space path loss (FSPL)</h3>
              <p>
                For a line-of-sight link in free space, the path loss in dB is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \( \text{FSPL(dB)} = 92.45 + 20\log_{10}(d_{\text{km}}) +
                  20\log_{10}(f_{\text{GHz}}) \)
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
                  where \( d_{\text{km}} \) is distance in kilometers and \(
                  f_{\text{GHz}} \) is frequency in gigahertz.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. EIRP and received power</h3>
              <p>
                The effective isotropic radiated power (EIRP) combines transmit
                power and transmit antenna gain:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \( \text{EIRP(dBW)} = P_t(\text{dBW}) + G_t(\text{dBi}) \)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The received power at the antenna input (ignoring polarization
                mismatch, etc.) is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \( P_r(\text{dBW}) = P_t + G_t + G_r - \text{FSPL} -
                  L_{\text{misc}} \)
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
                  where \( G_r \) is receive antenna gain and \( L_{\text{misc}}
                  \) groups all additional losses (feeder, pointing,
                  atmospheric, rain, polarization, implementation).
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Noise power, SNR and Eb/N0</h3>
              <p>Thermal noise power in a bandwidth \( B \) is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\( N = k T_{\text{sys}} B \)</p>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
                  where \( k = 1.38 \times 10^{-23} \,\text{J/K} \) is
                  Boltzmann's constant, \( T_{\text{sys}} \) is system noise
                  temperature in kelvin, and \( B \) is bandwidth in hertz.
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>In dB units:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \( N(\text{dBW}) = 10\log_{10}(k) +
                  10\log_{10}(T_{\text{sys}}) + 10\log_{10}(B) \)
                </p>
                <p>\( \text{SNR (C/N)} = P_r(\text{dBW}) - N(\text{dBW}) \)</p>
              </div>
              <p>The energy-per-bit to noise spectral density ratio is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \( E_b/N_0(\text{dB}) = \text{SNR(dB)} - 10\log_{10}(R_b/B) \)
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
                  where \( R_b \) is the data rate (bit/s). If \( R_b = B \),
                  then \( E_b/N_0 = \text{SNR} \).
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Fade margin</h3>
              <p>
                Given a required \( E_b/N_0 \) for your modulation and coding
                scheme, the fade margin is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \( \text{Fade margin} = E_b/N_0(\text{actual}) -
                  E_b/N_0(\text{required}) - L_{\text{impl}} \)
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
                  where \( L_{\text{impl}} \) is implementation loss in dB. A
                  positive margin (e.g., 3–10 dB) indicates a robust link under
                  typical fading and interference.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Typical values and design tips</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Satellite frequency bands:</strong> L-band (1–2 GHz),
                  S-band (2–4 GHz), C-band (4–8 GHz), Ku-band (12–18 GHz),
                  Ka-band (26–40 GHz).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>System noise temperature:</strong> 200–800 K for
                  satellite ground stations, lower for well-designed LNAs.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Required Eb/N0:</strong> ~3–5 dB for robust coded
                  QPSK, 7–10 dB for higher-order modulations.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Fade margin:</strong> 3–6 dB for relatively benign
                  links, 10–20 dB for high-availability or heavy rain regions at
                  Ka-band.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Limitations</h3>
              <p>
                This calculator assumes a single-hop, line-of-sight link with
                free-space propagation and aggregates all non-idealities into
                user-specified losses and noise temperature. For detailed rain
                attenuation, multipath, or interference analysis, you may need
                specialized propagation models or simulation tools.
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>
              <h3>Can I use this for terrestrial microwave links?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Set the distance to your path length, include terrain and
                clutter losses in
                <em>Other losses</em>, and use appropriate antenna gains and
                system noise temperature.
              </p>
              <h3>How do I choose bandwidth vs. data rate?</h3>
              <p>
                For many systems, the occupied RF bandwidth is close to the
                symbol rate. As a rough rule, you can set bandwidth ≈ data rate
                / spectral efficiency. If unsure, using the channel bandwidth is
                a reasonable starting point.
              </p>
